{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_018tj2hUmyJP89RSTkEFSgQ7","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze this task systematically. I need to write test plan behaviors for a Python automation that reviews PRs. The core functionality:\n1. Reads a PR\n2. Identifies problems in changed code\n3. Posts inline review comments at correct positions\n4. Creates a top-level summary comment\n5. Summary findings correspond to inline comments\n\nLet me think through each behavior:\n\n**Behavior 1: The review input is scoped to the lines that changed, not the full content of each modified file.**\n\nKey question: Could a mock miss this failure?\n- This is about reading the diff correctly from the PR API\n- The failure would manifest as: \"the review analyzed code that wasn't changed\" \n- A mock could easily miss this by just returning all file content\n- But the real failure: calling the real GitHub API or git diff command\n- This requires either:\n  - Real GitHub API call to get diff context\n  - Real git diff parsing\n  - Real filesystem with git repo\n\nThe failure boundary is: does the code correctly extract ONLY the changed lines from a diff?\n- Could mock miss it? Yes - a mock that returns full file content would still work with the review logic\n- Does it need real infrastructure? Yes - need real PR/diff to see the failure\n- This is System level because it requires:\n  - Real PR system (GitHub API) OR real git diff output\n  - Real filesystem state\n  \nActually, let me reconsider. The question is: what's the minimum test level to catch \"the review analyzed lines that weren't changed\"?\n- Mock the GitHub API to return a specific diff → Unit/Integration could catch this\n- The diff parsing itself is deterministic\n- You don't need a real GitHub API to test this - you can mock the API response with a real diff payload\n\nSo this could be Integration: mock the GitHub API with realistic diff data, verify the code only analyzes changed lines.\n\nBut could a pure mock miss the failure? \n- If you mock: `github_client.get_pr_diff()` to return a diff object\n\n\n- Then verify the review logic respects the diff boundaries, this catches the failure IF the diff mock is realistic\n\nThe key insight: the failure is \"the review reads beyond the diff boundary\". To catch this, I need a diff with lines both inside and outside the changed region, feed it to the review logic, and verify it only flags things in the changed region. This is achievable at Integration level with a mock GitHub API returning a realistic diff. The risk is that a mock could hide this if it doesn't capture real diff format quirks, but diff parsing is fundamentally deterministic.\n\nMinimum: Integration (mock GitHub API with realistic diff data)\n\n**Behavior 2: Inline comments are attached to the correct positions in the diff view on the pull request.**\n\nKey question: Could a mock miss this?\n- This is about posting comments to the right line numbers in the PR's diff view\n- The failure would be: comments appear on wrong lines or fail to post at all\n- A mock GitHub API could hide this if it doesn't validate line number constraints\n- The real failure requires understanding how GitHub's diff view maps line numbers\n- This needs either real GitHub API calls or a mock that enforces GitHub's actual line numbering rules\n\nThe actual failure only surfaces when posting to GitHub's real API with a real PR, or if the API format changed and the mock didn't catch it. This is System level because I need to post actual comments to a real PR and verify they appear in the correct diff positions.\n\nThe failure modes are: wrong line number generation, incorrect position format, GitHub API rejection, or the comment appearing at the wrong location in the UI. A mock can catch formatting issues and line number errors, but it won't catch API contract changes or how GitHub interprets the position. To reliably detect when inline comments attach to the wrong positions, I need the System level test with real GitHub infrastructure. The core issue is whether the failure—a comment posted at the wrong position—requires real GitHub infrastructure to catch. If I mock the API with proper position validation, I can verify the code passes the correct line number and format. That's Integration level. However, if my mock doesn't validate the position format itself, a real GitHub rejection could slip through undetected. The question becomes: can an in-process mock realistically validate position constraints, or does that require hitting the actual API? A mock that simply stores whatever position value it receives won't catch format errors that GitHub would reject. genetic level because the agent's ability to identify real defects depends on an actual AI/ML model processing real pull request diffs—a mock would only return predetermined responses and miss genuine failures. The behavior requires real infrastructure: the actual agent and LLM working on actual code changes.\n\nFor the fourth behavior, I need to verify the relationship between inline comments posted to the PR and findings in the top-level summary. A failure would occur if the summary lists a finding without a corresponding inline comment backing it up.\n\nThis is deterministic logic that could be tested at the integration level by mocking the GitHub API to capture all posts, then verifying each summary finding has a matching inline comment. However, there's a question about whether mocking GitHub is sufficient—if the behavior is specifically about findings actually being posted to the PR, then mocking might not fully validate that the posts succeeded in the real system.\n\nThe real failure mode to catch is when the agent generates multiple inline comments but only posts some of them. This requires either mocking GitHub and verifying all generated comments appear in the API calls, or posting to a real GitHub PR and confirming they all show up. Since the failure is about the code's posting logic rather than GitHub's behavior, integration testing with mocks should be adequate.\n\nFor the full end-to-end sequence—reading the diff, generating findings, posting inline comments, and posting the summary—this needs to work correctly for a real pull request without manual intervention.\n\nThe failure could break anywhere in the chain: diff reading, finding generation, posting comments, posting the summary, or the orchestration between steps. Catching a real failure requires the actual agent making decisions, the real GitHub API, and a real PR. This is a workflow test because it involves multiple agentic steps in sequence where each step's output feeds into the next, and a failure could hide in any step or in how they connect together. Mocking any component could mask a real problem, and the agent's decisions directly affect what gets posted downstream.\n\nNow considering the probability distribution across test levels for each behavior. The question is: what's the minimum level needed to catch a real failure for each specific behavior?\n\nFor the behavior \"scoped to changed lines\" - the core question is whether the code correctly extracts changed lines. Integration testing with a mocked GitHub API but realistic diff data could catch most failures here, though System testing with the real API might be necessary to catch edge cases in how GitHub formats diffs. Unit tests would only catch simple logic errors, agentic testing isn't really relevant since this isn't LLM-dependent, and workflow testing is overkill for this isolated behavior.\n\nFor inline comments at correct positions, the minimum level depends on the complexity of the position format. If it's straightforward (just a line number), Integration testing with mocked GitHub API calls could verify the code calculates and passes the right position. But if the format is complex or frequently changes, System testing with the real API becomes necessary to catch validation failures that wouldn't surface in mocks.\n\nFor identifying real defects, this is fundamentally an Agentic concern—the LLM's actual capability to find issues can't be tested without the real model. Consistency between summary and inline comments is deterministic logic that Integration can handle by mocking the API and verifying both outputs match. The full sequence completing is an end-to-end concern that likely requires System or Workflow level testing to ensure all steps execute properly. level is the minimum needed to catch this specific failure, not higher or lower.\n\nFor Behavior 2 (inline comments at correct positions), I'm reconsidering the confidence distribution. Unit testing seems unlikely to be sufficient on its own at 5%, while integration testing with proper mocks could reliably catch positioning issues at 40%. System-level testing would be most reliable at 50%, though agentic and workflow levels probably aren't necessary for this particular behavior. Let me recalibrate across both behaviors with this framing in mind. Behavior 1 (scoped to changed lines) would lean heavily toward integration at 75%, with system catching edge cases at 18%, and unit testing only marginally helpful at 5%.\n\nNow I need to identify which level I'm most confident in for each behavior. Behavior 1 points to integration, Behavior 2 to system, Behavior 3 (identifying real defects) strongly to agentic at 85%, Behavior 4 back to integration, and Behavior 5 (full sequence completion) to workflow at 60%.\n\nBefore finalizing these minimum levels, I should verify they're consistent with the self-check: could a real failure actually slip through at that level due to mocking or oversimplification? For Behavior 1, if I choose integration, I need to confirm that a diff-related failure wouldn't be masked by my test setup. The mock needs to capture all API interactions to catch this—it's about the code logic, not GitHub's behavior. All five behaviors check out as plan-consistent.\n\nNow I'm ready to structure the actual test plan. For each behavior, I need to specify the behavior ID, a clear description of what's being tested, identify the minimum test level required, explain why that level is necessary, describe how the test would work, confirm plan consistency, add any relevant notes, and estimate the probability distribution across all five test levels.\n\nStarting with the first behavior around scoped review analysis: the core failure would be if the review logic examines unchanged lines or misses changed ones entirely. This requires an Integration-level test because unit tests of diff parsing alone won't catch how the review logic actually applies those diff boundaries—things like off-by-one errors or incorrect region detection. A mocked GitHub API returning realistic diff structures can expose these scoping failures without needing the real GitHub API, since the scoping logic itself is deterministic once the diff structure is provided.\n\nFor the test itself, I'd mock GitHub to return a PR where lines 10-15 are changed while lines 1-9 and 16-20 remain unchanged. Then feed a file with identical issues scattered across all three regions to the review logic and verify it only flags the changed lines, ignoring the same issues elsewhere. This confirms the diff parsing correctly extracts the changed region and the review respects those boundaries.\n\nMoving to the second behavior about inline comment positioning: the failure mode here is comments being posted but attached to the wrong line or diff position. This requires System-level testing because the interaction between the review agent's comment generation and GitHub's API response for posting comments is where positioning errors surface—unit tests of comment formatting alone won't catch these failures. are positioned at the correct lines—for instance, a comment meant for line 42 should appear at line 42 in the UI without API errors. This requires running against an actual test repository and PR to validate real GitHub API behavior.\n\nMoving to the next behavior, identifying real defects in a PR with a known bug depends on the agent's actual capability to analyze code changes and recognize problematic patterns. The agent must successfully spot at least one genuine issue rather than generating false positives. This is fundamentally an agentic-level concern since it requires the review system to reason about code semantics and intent, not just structural validation. bugs to ensure the agent doesn't just get lucky on one case. I should also measure precision and recall—whether the agent catches all known bugs and avoids false positives.\n\nFor Behavior 4, the key issue is consistency between the summary findings and inline comments. Every finding in the top-level summary needs a matching inline comment, and vice versa. This is fundamentally a logic check rather than an LLM capability assessment, so it can be validated at the Integration level. The failure mode is straightforward: a finding appears in the summary without a corresponding inline comment posted to the code.\n\nTo test this, I'd mock the GitHub API to capture all comment posts—both inline and summary-level. After running the review, I can extract findings from the summary and cross-reference them against the recorded inline comments, verifying each finding has its match. I should also check for orphaned inline comments with no summary reference. Parametrized tests covering zero findings, single findings, and multiple findings would catch edge cases.\n\nThe consistency between inline and summary comments is deterministic and fully testable at the Integration level. Real GitHub interactions wouldn't reveal additional failure modes beyond this mapping logic itself.\n\nFor the end-to-end sequence, the pipeline has multiple dependencies: reading the diff feeds into agent analysis, which then drives inline comment posting, followed by the summary comment. Since agent analysis introduces non-determinism and actual GitHub API calls are involved, this requires Workflow-level testing to validate the full orchestration completes without breaking at any stage.\n\nA Unit or Integration test of individual components won't catch chain failures—like when agent output format doesn't align with the posting logic. System tests of isolated steps miss orchestration gaps, such as missing error handling between stages. Only running the complete flow with a real PR, actual agent execution, and live GitHub API interactions can surface end-to-end breakdowns.\n\nThe test should create or use an existing test PR and run the full review automation without mocks. Verify the PR diff loads correctly, the agent analyzes without errors, inline comments post successfully, summary comments appear, and everything runs hands-off with no manual intervention. Check the return code indicates success and all stages completed without partial failures. Run against PRs of different sizes and complexities to ensure no exceptions, timeouts, or stuck processes occur.\n\nNow reconsidering whether Integration testing might suffice for Behavior 2 with more rigorous design. The core failure mode involves the agent calculating comment positions that then fail when posted to GitHub—either rejected outright or placed incorrectly. Let me examine if Integration-level testing could actually catch this.\n\nFailure mode 1 (API rejection) could be caught with a mocked GitHub API that validates position format. Failure mode 2 (wrong visual placement) requires real GitHub interaction since the position interpretation logic is complex and unlikely to be perfectly replicated in a mock. The behavior specifically requires verifying \"correct positions in the diff view on the pull request,\" which demands actual GitHub API calls and real PR interaction to confirm visual placement. This confirms System level is necessary, not Integration.\n\nThe core question is what minimum infrastructure catches real failures. For this behavior, the actual failure is an inline comment appearing at the wrong position in the PR. A mocked API might catch code-level errors like incorrect position calculation or formatting, but it would miss GitHub API interpretation changes, format shifts, or UI rendering issues. Only real GitHub interaction with an actual PR can verify the complete end-to-end behavior.\n\nMy confidence assessment: System testing is most likely the minimum at 55%, since it validates against real GitHub. Integration with a sophisticated mock could work in some cases (35%), but there's meaningful risk of missing API-level changes. Unit, Workflow, and Agentic testing are unlikely to be sufficient (3-5% each).\n\nNow reconsidering the first behavior about scoped review input. The real failure would manifest if the review analyzes unchanged lines. This could stem from incorrect diff parsing or review logic that ignores diff boundaries. An integration test using a mocked GitHub API could catch the review logic bug by verifying the system respects changed line boundaries, but wouldn't catch if the actual GitHub API response format differs from what the mock assumes.\n\nSystem testing with real GitHub would catch both the logic issue and any edge cases in how GitHub formats diffs. Given this, I'm confident in the distribution: Integration at 75% since it covers the primary logic failure, System at 18% for real-world format variations, Unit at 5%, and Other at 2%.\n\nNow I need to verify the output format uses proper capitalization for the keys.\n\nChecking that all probability distributions sum to 1.0 across the five behaviors—they do. Ready to generate the final output.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13470,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13470},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":