orrect line/position in the PR diff view, as interpreted by GitHub.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"The failure is: the comment is posted to GitHub but appears at the wrong position in the PR UI, or GitHub API rejects the position format. Mocking the GitHub API (Integration) can verify that your code calculates and formats the position correctly, but it cannot verify that GitHub interprets that position as you intend or that the comment renders at the right place in the UI. The position format itself is an external contract that can evolve; GitHub's interpretation of 'position in diff' (commit hash, diff context lines, suggestion-only format) is a real-API behavior that only System-level testing reveals. A realistic mock reduces risk but does not eliminate it. Only posting a real comment to a real test PR can guarantee the failure is caught.","test_description":"Create or use a test PR with known changes to multiple files and lines. Run the full review logic on a real GitHub PR (not a mock). Capture the position coordinates your code generates for inline comments. Call the real GitHub API to post comments at those positions. Query the GitHub API to retrieve the posted comments and verify via the PR UI (or API response) that each comment appears attached to the correct line number in the diff. Assert that a comment intended for line 42 is attached to line 42 (not 41 or 43). Repeat for comments at multiple positions and in multiple files.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.35,"System":0.55,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The review agent identifies at least one real defect when analyzing a PR that contains a known introduced bug.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"The failure is: the agent fails to identify a real bug in the code (false negative) or identifies only false positives. This directly depends on the real agent's/LLM's reasoning quality. Mocking the agent with canned responses (Unit/Integration) does not test the agent's actual ability to detect defects. System-level testing of the agent in isolation on a single PR also does not reveal whether the agent generalizes to different bug types. Only running the real agent on a real PR with a real bug (Agentic level) validates that the agent is functionally capable of identifying real defects. Repeated tests with multiple bug types and PRs improve confidence.","test_description":"Create a test PR that introduces a specific, real bug (e.g., missing null check, unhandled exception in a new code path, off-by-one loop error, SQL injection vulnerability, race condition). Invoke the review agent/LLM on the full PR diff. Parse the agent's findings. Verify that at least one finding matches the known bug (by keyword match, line number, or semantic equivalence). Assert the finding is technically correct (not a false positive). Repeat with different bug types and severities to ensure the agent does not just get lucky on one case. Measure precision (ratio of correct findings to total findings) and recall (ratio of bugs found to bugs introduced).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.85,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"Every finding listed in the top-level summary comment corresponds to an inline comment that was posted; no orphaned findings appear in the summary without a matching inline comment.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure is: the summary mentions a finding but no corresponding inline comment was posted (or vice versa). This is a consistency check on deterministic code logic: the review logic must maintain the invariant that inline findings and summary findings are in sync. You can mock the GitHub API to intercept and record all comment posts (both inline and summary). Then you extract findings from the mocked summary comment and verify that each one has a matching inline-comment post (by ID, description, or line number). This logic is fully testable at Integration level without real GitHub API calls. Real GitHub API (System) adds no new failure detection for this specific check.","test_description":"Mock the GitHub API to record all comment posts (inline and summary). Run the full review logic to completion. Extract the list of findings from the mocked top-level summary comment (parse the comment text). Extract all inline comments from the mock call list. For each finding in the summary, verify a corresponding inline comment was posted (by matching finding ID, line number, or description). Assert no orphaned findings exist in the summary. Assert no orphaned inline comments exist (unless expected per design). Use parametrized tests to cover: 0 findings, 1 finding, N findings, multiple findings on the same line, findings in multiple files.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.15,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The full end-to-end sequence (read PR diff → analyze with agent → post inline comments → post summary comment) completes successfully without errors or manual intervention.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"The failure is: the pipeline breaks at any step. Each step depends on the prior step's output: diff must be readable → agent must complete analysis without error → inline comments must post successfully → summary must post successfully. The agent analysis is non-deterministic (Agentic level failure); real GitHub API calls are required (System-level concerns); and orchestration between steps can fail (missing error handling, timeout, cascading failures). A single-step test (Unit/Integration) misses failures in the chain (e.g., agent's output format does not match the posting code's expectations). System-level tests of individual steps miss orchestration failures. Only Workflow-level testing with a real PR, real agent running real analysis, and real GitHub API calls can catch end-to-end failures like 'agent succeeded but comment posting code crashed' or 'timeout between steps'.","test_description":"Create a test PR (or use a pre-existing one). Invoke the review automation end-to-end with no mocks: real GitHub API to fetch the PR, real agent to analyze the diff, real GitHub API to post comments. Verify: (1) PR diff is successfully read, (2) agent completes analysis without timeout or exception, (3) all inline comments are successfully posted to the PR, (4) top-level summary comment is successfully posted, (5) no manual steps are required (fully automated). Assert the automation process returns success status, all steps logged completion, no partial state left behind. Measure wall-clock execution time; assert it completes in a reasonable time window (no hangs). Test with PRs of varying sizes, code complexity, and bug distributions. Verify no unhandled exceptions, no orphaned processes, no timeout cascades.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.15,"Agentic":0.2,"Workflow":0.6}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13470,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13470},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a6d9db80-ad3c-4978-8065-5cfdb91fb86c","uuid":"5a7d150e-7446-488e-8db7-d8e284a4f16a"}
